
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dash` yek shell sade va sabok baraye UNIX-like system-ha ast. In shell be onvane `/bin/sh` dar Debian va Ubuntu estefade mishavad va baraye ejraye script-haye shell sari’ va ba masrafe kam memory monaseb ast.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-c command`  --> 📝 Dastoor ra az string ejra kon. Mesal: `dash -c 'echo Salam Donya'`
    🔹 `-n`         --> 🔍 Faghat syntax script ra check kon, vali ejra nakon. Mesal: `dash -n script.sh`
    🔹 `-v`         --> 🗣️ Har command ra ghabl az ejra chap kon (verbose mode). Mesal: `dash -v script.sh`
    🔹 `-x`         --> ⚙️ Har command va argument-haye aan ra qabl az ejra chap kon (trace mode). Mesal: `dash -x script.sh`
    🔹 `-s`         --> ⌨️ Command-ha ra az standard input bekhan. Mesal: `dash -s < script.sh`

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dash script.sh

    🔹 Script `script.sh` ra ba shell `dash` ejra kon.

    $ dash -c 'echo $PATH'

    🔹 Dastoor `echo $PATH` ra ba `dash` ejra kon.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dash -n script.sh

    🔹 Syntax `script.sh` ra check mikonad, be sharti ke khataee dar syntax nabashad chizi namayesh nemidahad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dash` command is a simple and lightweight shell for UNIX-like systems.  It is often used as `/bin/sh` on Debian and Ubuntu and is suitable for running shell scripts quickly and with low memory usage.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-c command`  --> 📝 Execute the command from a string. Example: `dash -c 'echo Hello World'`
    🔹 `-n`         --> 🔍 Only check the syntax of the script, but do not execute it. Example: `dash -n script.sh`
    🔹 `-v`         --> 🗣️ Print each command before executing it (verbose mode). Example: `dash -v script.sh`
    🔹 `-x`         --> ⚙️ Print each command and its arguments before executing it (trace mode). Example: `dash -x script.sh`
    🔹 `-s`         --> ⌨️ Read commands from standard input. Example: `dash -s < script.sh`

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dash script.sh

    🔹 Execute the script `script.sh` with the `dash` shell.

    $ dash -c 'echo $PATH'

    🔹 Execute the command `echo $PATH` with `dash`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dash -n script.sh

    🔹 Checks the syntax of `script.sh`.  If there are no syntax errors, nothing will be displayed.
